## 0.4.1
  * `clj-kondo-postedit` hook now runs clj-kondo from the edited file's own
    repo root instead of the hook's working directory. When editing across
    repos (the hook fires in one repo's session while the edited file lives in
    a sibling repo), clj-kondo previously discovered the session repo's
    `.clj-kondo/config.edn` and analysis cache — or none — and surfaced
    false-positive findings (unresolved symbols, type mismatches) that don't
    reflect the edited file's actual project config. Lints each file from its
    own `git rev-parse --show-toplevel` root.

## 0.4.0
  * Ship a baseline clj-kondo config with the plugin and a
    `/clojure-security:setup-clj-kondo` skill to pull it into a project.
    The config is security-tuned, not skeleton-silencing: it escalates
    `:type-mismatch` and `:refer-all` to `:error` and surfaces
    `:unused-binding`, `:shadowed-var`, and `:unused-private-var` as
    `:warning` — the sloppy code where security bugs hide. Resolution
    linters (`:unresolved-*`) stay at clj-kondo defaults because the
    per-edit hook lints a single file without classpath analysis;
    `:unresolved-symbol` carries Speclj / c3kit.wire / c3kit.apron.log
    library-macro excludes only. If a `.clj-kondo/config.edn` already
    exists, the skill shows a diff and asks whether to overwrite, skip,
    or merge.
  * `SessionStart` hook now suggests running
    `/clojure-security:setup-clj-kondo` when a Clojure project has no
    `.clj-kondo/config.edn`. Informational, folded into the existing
    toolchain notice — one message per session, no nag, no blocking.

## 0.3.2
  * `SessionStart` hook now adds `.security-session-start-sha` to the
    project's `.gitignore` when it creates the session-start marker, so
    the marker is never accidentally committed. Idempotent (skips if the
    entry already exists) and inserts a trailing newline first when the
    existing `.gitignore` lacks one. Matched by basename so the pattern
    works regardless of where `.gitignore` sits relative to `.claude/`.

## 0.3.1
  * Fix plugin install failure: wrap `hooks/hooks.json` contents in a
    top-level `"hooks"` object so it matches the current Claude Code
    plugin schema. Previously the loader reported
    `expected: record, path: ["hooks"], received: undefined` and
    refused to register any of the plugin's hooks.

## 0.3.0
  * `SessionStart` hook now audits the security toolchain in Clojure
    projects and injects a `additionalContext` notice listing missing
    tools, their role, and an install hint. Checks `clj-kondo`,
    `gitleaks`, `clj-holmes` (binary + rules dir at
    `$CLJ_HOLMES_RULES_DIR` or `/tmp/clj-holmes-rules`), `nvd-clojure`,
    and `jq`. Skipped silently in non-Clojure projects. Surfaces once
    per session — no per-edit / per-stop noise. Rationale: silent
    no-ops on missing tools were invisible; users could ship code
    believing the hooks had cleared it when in fact the relevant
    scanner had never run.

## 0.2.0
  * `PreToolUse` backstop on `git commit`. Matches the `Bash` tool with
    a command starting `git commit` (not `git commit-tree`,
    `git commit --help`, etc.). Runs gitleaks in native `protect --staged`
    mode against the index, and clj-holmes against the staged content of
    Clojure files (uses `git show :path` so partial-stage findings are
    caught even when the working tree was cleaned). Exit 0 lets the
    commit through; exit 2 blocks it with a structured stderr report.
    The skill explicitly frames this hook as "for Claude, not for humans
    with full context" — humans can run the commit themselves to override.
  * Fix clj-holmes invocation in `security-stop.sh` and `commit-backstop.sh`.
    Both were using `clj-holmes scan --path` (wrong flag) and parsing free
    text with a too-broad grep, producing false-positive findings from
    the help text. Now uses `clj-holmes scan -p <dir> -d <rules> -t json
    -o <file>` and parses the JSON structure (per-rule × per-finding).
    Rules dir resolves from `$CLJ_HOLMES_RULES_DIR` or defaults to
    `/tmp/clj-holmes-rules`. Skips silently if the rules dir is missing
    (run `clj-holmes fetch-rules` to populate).

## 0.1.0
  * Initial scaffold. `clojure-security` skill with vulnerability-class
    reference for Clojure / ClojureScript codebases: read-string / EDN
    reader exploits, Java deserialization sinks, dynamic code execution,
    JVM CVE inheritance (Log4Shell-class), XML / YAML parsing, SQL
    injection via string concatenation, Hiccup / Selmer template
    injection, CLJS XSS surfaces, atom check-then-act races, reflection
    in security-sensitive paths, spec / Malli data leaks in error
    responses, and macros consuming runtime user input. Includes
    grep/Semgrep starter patterns, false-positive heuristics, severity
    triage, investigation order, and tool-finding interpretation
    (clj-kondo, clj-holmes, nvd-clojure, gitleaks, Semgrep).
  * `/security-audit` slash command. Scope arg: `all` (default),
    `staged`, `diff`, or a path. Runs the skill's quick-wins pattern
    sweep, invokes installed tools best-effort (clj-kondo, clj-holmes,
    gitleaks, nvd-clojure, semgrep), triages each finding through the
    skill's investigation order, and produces a structured report
    grouped by severity. Surfaces findings only — never auto-fixes.
  * `PostToolUse` hook on Edit / Write / MultiEdit for
    `.clj`/`.cljs`/`.cljc`/`.edn`/`.bb` files. Runs `clj-kondo` against
    the edited file(s) only. Sub-second (~20ms on a small file). Exit
    semantics: 0 silent on clean / non-Clojure / missing tools; 1 for
    warning-only findings (non-blocking); 2 for error-level findings
    (Claude must address before continuing). Degrades to silent no-op
    if `clj-kondo` or `jq` is not installed. Bash-3.2 compatible
    (macOS default). Iteration target: cleancoders `poker` repo.
  * `SessionStart` hook records the HEAD SHA into
    `.claude/.security-session-start-sha` so the Stop hook has a stable
    diff base on default branches. `SessionEnd` hook removes the marker.
    Both no-op if the cwd is not a git repo.
  * `Stop` hook runs `clj-holmes` (Clojure SAST patterns) and `gitleaks`
    (secret scanning) against the session diff. Diff scope tiered:
    (1) feature branch — merge-base with `origin/<default>`, plus
    uncommitted + untracked; (2) default branch with marker —
    `marker..HEAD` + uncommitted + untracked; (3) no marker — uncommitted
    + untracked only; (4) not a git repo — skip. Exit 0 silent on
    clean / no diff / missing tools / not git; exit 2 blocks the Stop
    and surfaces a structured findings report on stderr so Claude must
    address findings before the turn can end. Reentrancy (`stop_hook_active`)
    re-blocks with an explicit notice — override escalates to the human.
    Findings layout: gitleaks first (secrets are highest-impact), then
    clj-holmes; both link back to the `clojure-security` skill's
    investigation order.
